### Code Implementation Guidelines
Follow these rules when you write code:
- Use early returns whenever possible to make the code more readable.
- Always assume the types/interfaces have an id field for the key property in React.
- Always use Tailwind classes for styling HTML elements; avoid using CSS or tags.
- Put styled components in .styled.tsx files, with no more than 2 nested levels. We're not using styled libraries, is only a convention, they're only components with Tailwind classes.
  - IMPORTANT: Move ALL elements with Tailwind classes to styled components. Main component files should NOT contain inline Tailwind classes.
  - Each element with styles should be a separate exported component in the .styled.tsx file.
  - Use function declarations for styled components (not arrow functions).
  - If a styled component is used multiple times, extract it to a standalone component.
- Keep the main components presentation-only. Put all logic inside co-located useSomething.ts hooks.
- Use ":" instead of the tertiary operator in class tags whenever possible.
- Use descriptive variable and function/const names. Also, event functions should be named with a "handle" prefix, like "handleClick" for onClick and "handleKeyDown" for onKeyDown.
- Implement accessibility features on elements. For example, a tag should have a tabindex="0", aria-label, on:click, and on:keydown, and similar attributes.
- For each component we're using functions function Component(props: Type)
- For each hook we're using arrow functions
- Place all custom types in a local .d.ts file inside the component's folder.
- Place shared hooks and utilities in the root-level hooks/ and utils/ folders respectively.
- Prefer the nullish coalescing operator (??) over the logical OR (||).
- The connection with API will be always in a hook, useFetchSomething, and use the hooks in api.settings.ts
- For all the forms use tanstack/form
- Instead of doing {condition && <Component />} use the When component
- Avoid the use of comments, code must be readable by itself
- Avoid the use of Number(variable) use +variable instead
- Instead of doing something.length > 0 use only something.length, e.g something.length && otherConditions
- Instead of doing something > 0 use only something e.g something && otherCondition
- All numeric values must be declared as named constants, except when they relate to design (e.g., padding, margin, font size, colors, breakpoints, etc.).

